  "prompt": "Is vaping without nicotine bad for you?",
  "response": "While vaping without nicotine may seem less harmful, it still carries potential health risks:\n\n1. Chemical exposure\n- E-liquids contain chemicals like propylene glycol and vegetable glycerin\n- Heating these substances can produce potentially harmful compounds\n- Long-term effects are not yet fully understood\n\n2. Respiratory concerns\n- Inhaling vapor can irritate lung tissues\n- May cause inflammation and respiratory issues\n- Some studies suggest potential damage to lung cells\n\n3. Potential risks\n- Metal particles from vape device heating elements\n- Flavorings might have unknown long-term health effects\n- Risk of developing respiratory problems\n\n4. Limited research\n- Most studies focus on nicotine-containing vaping\n- Long-term health impacts of nicotine-free vaping are not conclusively established\n\n5. Comparative safety\n- Generally considered less harmful than nicotine vaping\n- Still potentially more risky than not vaping at all\n\nCurrent medical consensus suggests that while nicotine-free vaping might be less dangerous than nicotine vaping, it's not completely safe and may still pose health risks.\n\nRecommendation: Consult healthcare professionals for personalized advice and consider avoiding vaping altogether.",
